'''Daniel Alexander Mintz''' (born September 25, 1981) is an [[United States|American]] comedian, voice actor and writer<ref name="danmintz.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.danmintz.com/bio.php|title=Bio - Dan Mintz - The Stranger|website=www.danmintz.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> best known for his role as Bob's oldest daughter Tina Belcher on the animated show ''[[Bob's Burgers]]''.<ref name="danmintz.com"/> As a comedian, he is known for his extremely [[deadpan]] delivery, keeping his eyes fixed straight ahead and never looking toward the camera or audience.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/10/comedian-dan-mintz-interview-talking-bobs-burgers-mulaney-nathan-for-you/381396/|title=The Deadpan Voice of the Moment|last=Sims|first=David|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=14 October 2014|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Born to a Jewish family, Mintz grew up in [[Anchorage, Alaska]].<ref name="danmintz.com"/> He is a graduate of [[Harvard University]], where he wrote for ''[[The Harvard Lampoon]]''.
==Career== He landed his first writing job at [[Comedy Central]]'s ''[[Crank Yankers]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cc.com/shows/crank-yankers|title=Crank Yankers|website=Comedy Central|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> then worked on ''[[Last Call with Carson Daly]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbo.com/luckylouie/cast/crew/dan_mintz.html|title=HBO: Dan Mintz, Staff Writer - Lucky Louie|first=|last=HBO|website=wayback.archive.org|accessdate=4 August 2017|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070314211034/http://www.hbo.com/luckylouie/cast/crew/dan_mintz.html|archivedate=14 March 2007|df=}}</ref> He has written for ''[[The Andy Milonakis Show]]'', ''[[Human Giant]]'', ''[[Lucky Louie]]'', ''[[Important Things with Demetri Martin]]'', ''[[Jon Benjamin Has a Van]]'', ''[[Nick Swardson's Pretend Time]]'', ''[[Nathan For You]]'', ''[[The Awesomes]]'' and ''[[Mulaney]]''.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} His writing credits also include the ''[[Bob's Burgers]]'' episode titled "The Equestranauts".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/bobs-burgers-equestranauts-203399|title=Bob’s Burgers: "The Equestranauts"|date=13 April 2014|publisher=|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>
On May 16, 2007, Mintz appeared on ''[[Late Night with Conan O'Brien]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/late-night-conan-obrien/episodes/100252/12/|title=Late Night with Conan O'Brien|website=TVGuide.com|accessdate=22 May 2018}}</ref> His standup comedy appeared on the comedy compilation CD ''[[Comedy Death-Ray (album)|Comedy Death-Ray]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Comedy-Death-Ray/dp/B000X6SMYW|title=Comedy Death Ray|publisher=|accessdate=4 August 2017|via=Amazon}}</ref> and a special for ''[[Comedy Central Presents]]'' aired on March 28, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cc.com/episodes/mg4cp1/comedy-central-presents-cc-presents--dan-mintz-season-12-ep-1209|title=Comedy Central Presents - Dan Mintz - Comedy Central|website=Comedy Central|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> In February 2013, he performed standup on ''[[Late Show With David Letterman]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bing.com/videos/search?q=dan+mintz+david+letterman&view=detail&mid=30CFE3A546BA34CBBE6130CFE3A546BA34CBBE61&FORM=VIRE|title=dan mintz david letterman - Bing video|website=www.bing.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> He recorded a standup album, ''The Stranger'', at Comedy Works in Denver in July 2013. The album was released in 2014 through Comedy Central Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://danmintznews.tumblr.com/post/99407442592/hi-my-album-the-stranger-is-out-today-i-hope-you|title=Untitled — Hi, my album The Stranger is out today, I hope you...|website=Untitled|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>
==Personal life== Mintz resides in [[Los Angeles, California]]. Mintz married fellow comedian Margie Kment on May 29, 2011.{{Citation needed|reason=reference did not mention Dan Mintz here|date=May 2018}}
